{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476909"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:53:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:53:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13990"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13990"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.14,0.08,0.03,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6624"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49023"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6624"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13990"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34041"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1194"},{"type":"tags","id":"1396"},{"type":"tags","id":"1976"},{"type":"tags","id":"2357"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13447"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44191"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44967"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49023"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parent two days after falling face-first onto a concrete floor while playing. He complains of persistent nasal pain and difficulty breathing through his nose. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is mild external nasal swelling and tenderness. Anterior rhinoscopy reveals bilateral swelling of the nasal septum, partially obstructing both nasal passages.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate incision and drainage","Application of topical decongestants","Nasal packing and discharge home","Oral antibiotics and follow-up in one week","Observation and reassurance"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a scenario suggestive of a septal haematoma following nasal trauma in a child. The bilateral swelling of the nasal septum partially obstructing both nasal passages, coupled with the history of recent nasal trauma, points towards this diagnosis. The most appropriate next step in management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmediate incision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E. Septal haematoma is a medical emergency that requires prompt intervention to prevent serious complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotics and follow-up in one week\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate management for a suspected septal haematoma. While antibiotics may be prescribed after drainage to prevent infection, they are not a substitute for drainage. Delaying treatment for a week could lead to cartilage necrosis and permanent nasal deformity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApplication of topical decongestants\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the underlying haematoma and could potentially mask symptoms, leading to delayed diagnosis and treatment. Decongestants are not indicated in the management of septal haematoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasal packing and discharge home\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate for a suspected septal haematoma. Packing would not drain the haematoma and could exacerbate the problem by increasing pressure on the septal cartilage. Moreover, discharging the patient without addressing the potential haematoma could lead to serious complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation and reassurance\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate for managing a suspected septal haematoma. This approach would likely result in cartilage necrosis and subsequent saddle nose deformity, which can have significant functional and cosmetic implications for the child.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to managing septal haematoma is early recognition and prompt drainage. After drainage, the nose is typically packed to prevent re-accumulation of the haematoma, and antibiotics are often prescribed. Close follow-up is essential to ensure proper healing and to monitor for complications. In children, septal haematomas can be particularly problematic as they can affect normal nasal and facial growth if not managed appropriately.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Septal haematoma is a serious complication of nasal trauma that requires urgent drainage to prevent cartilage necrosis and saddle nose deformity.","Nasal septal haematoma typically presents with bilateral nasal obstruction and swelling of the nasal septum.","Early recognition and management of septal haematoma is crucial to prevent long-term complications in children."],"references":["Schwartz RH, Pugash RA. Nasal trauma and fractures in children and adolescents. UpToDate. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/nasal-trauma-and-fractures-in-children-and-adolescents?search=septal%20haematoma\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1%7E150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34041"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13990"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34041"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-22T14:44:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-04T14:52:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6624"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49023"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},